{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17513706","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17513706"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T13:13:02+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T13:13:02+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12194"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"12194","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/12194"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.04,0.19,0.04,0.72,0.01]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4722"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"53446"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4722","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4722"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12194"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"38912"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"22"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"295"},{"type":"tags","id":"1189"},{"type":"tags","id":"4578"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4980"},{"type":"tags","id":"4985"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"9208"},{"type":"tags","id":"9209"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11634"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"},{"type":"tags","id":"12807"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"7422"},{"type":"contributions","id":"7573"},{"type":"contributions","id":"30111"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42714"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43299"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"53446","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/53446"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 19-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department with right lower quadrant pain and a 24-hour history of nausea and vomiting. She felt some generalised abdominal discomfort yesterday but now on presentation the pain is severe and localised. The patient has felt feverish. She denies changes to bowel motions, dysuria, abnormal vaginal discharge or bleeding.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EShe had a Mirena intrauterine device inserted four weeks ago for contraception and takes sertraline for generalised anxiety disorder. She has no known allergies. She has never had surgery. She is sexually active with her boyfriend of two months.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears distressed by pain. She has a BMI of 23 kg/m2. Her pulse rate is 100/min, blood pressure 108/82 mmHg, respiratory rate 18/min, temperature 37.8\u00b0C and oxygen saturation 99% on room air. She is tender to light palpation over the right lower quadrant with rebound tenderness and percussion tenderness. Urinalysis dipstick is unremarkable.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most important next investigation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Full blood count, C-reactive protein, electrolytes, urea, creatinine, and liver function tests","Formal abdominal and transvaginal pelvic ultrasound","Abdominal CT","Urine or serum beta-hCG","High vaginal swab"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis is a sexually active female patient of reproductive age presenting with lower abdominal pain and potential haemodynamic instability. The patient\u0027s tachycardia may be a response to pain/anxiety and the blood pressure may be a normal variant in a young, thin woman. However, these vital signs may also indicate acute haemorrhage with \u0026lt;15% blood loss due to a ruptured ectopic pregnancy. Ectopic pregnancy must be ruled out with a \u003Cstrong\u003Eurine beta-hCG or serum beta-hCG\u003C/strong\u003E. Where a urine beta-hCG is positive, a quantitative serum beta-hCG is usually required to guide further management. While the presence of an IUD is generally protective against pregnancy, it\u0027s important to note that the Mirena was inserted only four weeks ago. There\u0027s a possibility that the patient could have been pregnant at the time of insertion, or that the IUD failed to prevent implantation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe reality of clinical practice, given situations such as described in this scenario, is that several investigations will be done rapidly. However, the priority must be to consider and exclude ectopic pregnancy. Beta-hCG estimation will provide a more accurate determination of pregnancy than ultrasound imaging.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBlood investigations\u003C/strong\u003E will be very important in this patient; however it is essential that pregnancy is excluded first to guide management.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIt would be very reasonable to perform a formal pelvic and abdominal \u003Cstrong\u003Eultrasound\u003C/strong\u003E in this patient to investigate differentials such as appendicitis, pelvic inflammatory disease, ovarian cyst rupture, ovarian torsion. However a formal ultrasound would not be performed until pregnancy is ruled out. A point of care ultrasound scan \u003Cstrong\u003E(POCUS) \u003C/strong\u003Ewould be a useful bedside investigation in this patient to determine if there was free abdominal fluid however this was not listed as an investigation that could be chosen in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Ehigh vaginal swab\u003C/strong\u003E should be performed based on further history from the patient. If she or her partner have not had recent STI testing then it would be plausible to assess for pelvic inflammatory disease in this patient.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAbdominal CT\u003C/strong\u003E would typically be avoided in women of childbearing age to avoid unnecessary radiation exposure. A pelvic and abdominal ultrasound would be used first line to gain imaging.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Ectopic pregnancy must be ruled out in a sexually active female with lower abdominal pain and suspected haemodynamic instability, even with recent IUD insertion.","Recent IUD insertion does not completely exclude the possibility of pregnancy or ectopic pregnancy."],"references":["Ectopic pregnancy and miscarriage Diagnosis and initial management in early pregnancy of ectopic pregnancy and miscarriage [Internet]. 2012. Available from: https://ranzcog.edu.au/wp-content/uploads/2022/05/Ectopic-pregnancy-and-miscarriage.pdf"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"38912"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12194"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"38912","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/38912"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-09-21T13:46:44+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-09-21T13:48:04+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4722"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"53446"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"22","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/22"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf53","name":"Gynaecology","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"3"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"item